window.docContents[94].resolve({"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Results-from-external-Lean-projects/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Results-from-external-Lean-projects":{"contents":"The nodes below are informal: the external projects are built against Mathlib versions that\ndiffer from AINTLIB's, so they carry no (lean := …) reference. Each records where the result\nis formalised, an exact-source permalink to the recorded commit, and whether that formalisation\nis sorry-free or still in progress. Both repositories are public.\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Algebraic Number Theory","header":"3.13. Results from external Lean projects","id":"/Algebraic-Number-Theory/Results-from-external-Lean-projects/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Algebraic-Number-Theory--Results-from-external-Lean-projects"},"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series--Supporting-Property-of-the-Newton-Polygon":{"contents":"The Newton polygon () is well-formed and its segments are supporting. A\nNewtonPolygonData is well-formed when consecutive segments share a vertex, segment slopes are\nnon-decreasing, and any final ray's slope is at least the last segment slope; the empty polygon (for\na constant or zero series) is well-formed. Each segment is tight — its right endpoint lies exactly\non the line extending it — and supporting: writing  for the slope set \nfrom a vertex , every later lattice point lies on or above the line of slope ,\n\nFormalised in NewtonPolys: NewtonPolygon.minSlope_supporting, NewtonPolygon.Segment.tight_of_slope, NewtonPolygon.achievingSet_onLine, NewtonPolygon.emptyPolygon_wellFormed — sorry-free.\n\nTightness (Segment.tight_of_slope) is the computation that, with the segment's own slope\n, the value  equals ; it is closed by\nfield_simp; ring after clearing the nonzero denominator . The supporting property\n(minSlope_supporting) is the heart: the real slope to any later point  belongs to the\nslope set , hence is  by csInf_le (using  bounded below); since\n, multiplying through and rearranging by linarith gives ,\nwhich is the infimum characterisation of the slope geometrically. Points achieving the minimum slope\nlie exactly on the line (achievingSet_onLine), the same field_simp; ring computation as\ntightness. Well-formedness of the empty polygon (emptyPolygon_wellFormed) is immediate, all four\nclauses being vacuous. (The project proves these supporting facts about the rotating-line step; it\ndoes not prove that the fully iterated buildNewtonPolygon output is well-formed.)\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Diophantine Equations and Transcendence\u0009Newton polygons of p-adic power series","header":"9.7.3. Supporting Property of the Newton Polygon","id":"/Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence/Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Diophantine-Equations-and-Transcendence--Newton-polygons-of-p-adic-power-series--Supporting-Property-of-the-Newton-Polygon"},"/Fermat___s-Last-Theorem-and-Regular-Primes/Stickelberger___s-theorem-and-the-Herbrand-bridge/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Fermat___s-Last-Theorem-and-Regular-Primes--Stickelberger___s-theorem-and-the-Herbrand-bridge":{"contents":"\n\n\n\n\n\n","context":"AINTLIB — An Atlas of Number Theory in Lean\u0009Fermat's Last Theorem and Regular Primes","header":"8.10. Stickelberger's theorem and the Herbrand bridge","id":"/Fermat___s-Last-Theorem-and-Regular-Primes/Stickelberger___s-theorem-and-the-Herbrand-bridge/#AINTLIB-___-An-Atlas-of-Number-Theory-in-Lean--Fermat___s-Last-Theorem-and-Regular-Primes--Stickelberger___s-theorem-and-the-Herbrand-bridge"}});